{"title_page": "Peter Canavan", "text_new": "{{for|the Garda officer|Peter P. Canavan}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox Gaelic Athletic Association player\n|image             = Peter Canavan - SFC 2005 cc 3.0.jpg\n|caption           = Canavan lifting the [[Sam Maguire Cup]] in 2003\n|name              = Peter Canavan\n|irish             = Peadar \u00d3 Ceannabh\u00e1in\n|nickname          = Peter 'The Great',<ref>{{Cite news|last=O'Sullivan |first=Jim |title=Peter the Great ready to answer Tyrone's call |date=19 June 2004 |newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]] |url=http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2004/06/19/story757189885.asp |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929145520/http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2004/06/19/story757189885.asp |archivedate=29 September 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=SundayTimes /><br/>'Petrol Pete'\n| feet             = 5\n| inches           = 9\n|occupation        = Teacher<ref name=program />\n|sport             = Gaelic football\n|code              = Football\n|county            = Tyrone\n|province          = Ulster\n|clposition        = Forward\n|club              = Errigal Ciaran \n|clyears           = 1990\u20132007\n|clapps(points)    = \n|clcounty          = 6\n|clprovince        = 2\n|clubs             = [[Errigal Ciar\u00e1n GAC]]\n|counties          = Tyrone\n|icposition        = Forward\n|icyears           = 1989\u20132005\n|icapps(points)    = 49 (9\u2013191 (218))<ref name= UlsterScorers />\n|icprovince        = 5\n|icallireland      = 2\n|allstars          = 6\n|nfl               = 2\n|icupdate          = (22:03, 21 December 2006 (UTC))<ref name=\"TeamTalk\" />\n|clupdate          = (15:04, 10 January 2007 (UTC)))<ref name=\"TeamTalk\" />\n|birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1971|04|09}}\n|birth_place       = [[Ballygawley, County Tyrone|Ballygawley]], [[County Tyrone]], Northern Ireland\n}}\n'''Peter Canavan''' (born 9 April 1971) is a former [[Irish people|Irish]] [[Gaelic football]] player, [[Manager (Gaelic games)|manager]] and pundit.\n\nHe played inter-county football for [[Tyrone GAA|Tyrone]], and is one of the most decorated players in the game's history, winning two [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]] medals, six [[List of All Stars Awards winners (football)|All Stars Awards]] (more than any other Ulster player, and joint third overall),<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.unison.ie/irish_independent/stories.php3?ca=37&si=1514357&issue_id=13331 | title = Big three sweep awards boards | accessdate=25 January 2007 | date=26 November 2005 | author = Martin Breheny | publisher= [[Irish Independent]] Online}}</ref> four [[Ulster Senior Football Championship|provincial titles]], and two [[National Football League (Ireland)|National Leagues]] and several under-age and club championship medals. He represented [[Ireland international rules football team|Ireland]] in the [[International Rules Series]] on several occasions from 1998 until 2000.<ref name=interRules/> He is considered one of the great players of the last twenty years by commentators such as John Haughey of the [[BBC]],<ref name=PeterBio>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/4284352.stm | title= Canavan's remarkable career| accessdate= 25 January 2007 | author = John Haughey| work = [[BBC Sport]] | date = 26 September 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.anfearrua.com/ViewSectionDetail.asp?docid=1235 |title= Two Bald Eagles: Peter The Great and Lion Hearted Leo |accessdate= 25 January 2007 |date= 3 October 2003 |author= 'Press Box Lad' |publisher= An Fear Rua |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070406040900/http://www.anfearrua.com/ViewSectionDetail.asp?docid=1235 |archive-date= 6 April 2007 |url-status= dead }}</ref> and in 2009, he was named in the ''[[Sunday Tribune]]''{{'}}s list of the ''125 Most Influential People in GAA History''.<ref name=\"125 tribune\">{{cite news |first=Enda |last=McEvoy |author2=Kieran Shannon, Dave Hannigan (and PJ Cunningham, Malachy Clerkin and Pat Nugent) |title=125 Most Influential People in GAA History |work=[[Sunday Tribune]] |date=4 January 2009 |accessdate=20 January 2009 |url=http://www.tribune.ie/article/2009/jan/04/125-most-influential-people-in-gaa-history-125-101 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090809014716/http://www.tribune.ie/article/2009/jan/04/125-most-influential-people-in-gaa-history-125-101 |archivedate=9 August 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHis scoring record of 218 points is the second highest of all time in the [[Ulster Senior Football Championship]].<ref name=UlsterScorers>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/low/northern_ireland/the_championship/5192032.stm |title= Ulster's hot-shots |accessdate=25 January 2007 | date=18 July 2006 | work = [[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> His early high scoring rate, when he would often be Tyrone's best performer<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/2011209.stm |title= Peter's loss lamented| accessdate= 29 April 2007 | author = Jerome Quinn | date = 27 May 2002 | work=BBC News}}</ref> \u2013 particularly in the [[1995 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final]] when he scored eleven of Tyrone's twelve points\u2014led to claims that Tyrone was a \"one-man show,\" and that the team was too dependent on him, particularly in his early career.<ref name=Eyesore >{{cite news | url= http://www.unison.ie/irish_independent/stories.php3?ca=95&si=1446552&issue_id=12836 | title = Tyrone and Canavan came up short in 'eyesore' final| accessdate= 25 January 2007 | newspaper = [[Irish Independent]] | date = 7 August 2005 | author = Sean Ryan}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | title = Gormley chases double with help from Canavan | newspaper = [[The Belfast Telegraph]] | date= 24 June 1996 | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref><ref name=\"GL_17/10/08\">{{cite news |first=Alan |last=Rodgers |title=Candid Canavan |url= |work=Gaelic Life |publisher= |date=17 October 2008 |pages=20\u201321 }}</ref>\n\nSince retiring as a player he has managed the [[Fermanagh GAA|Fermanagh]] inter-county Gaelic football team (2011\u20132013).\n\n==Personal life==\nCanavan is from Glencull, near [[Ballygawley, County Tyrone|Ballygawley]], County Tyrone<ref name=\"GL_17/10/08\"/> and was the tenth of eleven children.<ref name=SundayTimes>{{Cite news | last =Walsh | first =David | title = Gaelic games | newspaper = [[The Sunday Times]] | date = 28 August 1996 | postscript =<!--None-->}}</ref> His older brother, [[Pascal Canavan|Pascal]], played with him on the Tyrone panel for most of the 1990s. He is married to Finola (sister of former Tyrone team-mate Ronan McGarrity<ref name=\"GL_17/10/08\"/>), and has four children, Aine, Claire, Darragh and Ruairi, and has been a Physical Education teacher in Holy Trinity College, [[Cookstown, County Tyrone|Cookstown]], throughout most of his career (Gaelic games are amateur sports).<ref name=\"GL_17/10/08\"/><ref name=UUJ>{{cite web|url=http://news.ulster.ac.uk/releases/2003/955.html |title=University To Honour Ulster Sporting Heroes Canavan And Humphreys |accessdate=25 January 2007 |date=30 October 2003 |publisher=[[University of Ulster]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303183420/http://news.ulster.ac.uk/releases/2003/955.html |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref> While there, he taught [[Eoin Mulligan]] his point-taking technique, and the pair have been known in the media as 'master and student' ever since, particularly by television commentators.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sportacademy/hi/sa/special_events/gaelic_sports/newsid_3135000/3135296.stm | title =Learning at school| accessdate=2 May 2007 | work = [[BBC Sport]] | date=24 September 2003}}</ref>\n\nHe writes a column for the [[Gaelic games]] magazine, ''[[Hogan Stand]]''<ref>{{cite magazine | url= http://www.hoganstand.com/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=46266 | title= Canavan's Hogan Stand column regarding the decision by the GAA to abolish Rule 42 |accessdate= 25 January 2007 | date = 10 May 2005 | magazine = [[Hogan Stand]]}}</ref> and the Northern Ireland edition of ''[[The Daily Mirror]]''.<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/northernireland/2006/11/03/football-when-geezer-exploded-it-shook-us-up-89520-18037987/ | title = When Geezer exploded it shook us up | author = Peter Canavan | accessdate = 26 August 2007 | newspaper = [[The Daily Mirror]] | postscript= <!--None-->}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> and in 2008, Canavan joined [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]] as a football pundit for their first year of broadcasting live GAA matches.<ref>{{Cite journal | url = http://www.tv3.ie/pr_sub.php?type=1&view_pr=55 | title = TV3 Announce GAA line up for the 2009 Championship season | publisher = [[TV3 (Ireland)]] | author = TV3 press release | date = 26 May 2009 | accessdate = 15 January 2010 | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, just over a week before Tyrone's Ulster final appearance against [[Down GAA|Down]], Canavan's father, Se\u00e1n, died. It came as a shock to Canavan, who had thought his father (who was already in hospital) was getting better. He decided to play in the match, stating that he knew, subconsciously \"[he] was going to be playing in the Ulster final all along and Daddy certainly wouldn't have wanted [him] to do anything but play.\"<ref>{{cite book | first=Peter | last=Canavan | title=Every Step We Took. 2003 \u2013 A Football Odyssey | publisher=All Star Print Ltd. | location=Omagh, Northern Ireland | year=2004 | isbn=0-9546616-0-5 | page = 46}}</ref>\n\nCanavan has suffered from [[asthma]] since he was a child, and has battled throughout his career to control the ailment. He told the Asthma Society of Ireland, \"I thought to myself, this is something that I am just going to have to put up with.\" In later years, however, improved medication has afforded Canavan what he described as, \"a better quality of life\".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.irishhealth.com/clin/asthma/canavan.html |title=Peter Canavan \u2013 Life With Asthma |accessdate=25 January 2007 | publisher = irishhealth.com}}</ref>\n\n==Under-age career==\nTo play for an [[GAA county|inter-county GAA team]], Canavan had to work around a [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA) bylaw, because of a dispute in his parish, [[Errigal Ciar\u00e1n]]. Two clubs claimed to represent the parish, the established Ballygawley St. Ciaran's club and the newly formed club, then called Errigal Ciaran Naomh Malachai. Players from the Errigal team were not recognised as being GAA members, because the club failed to register correctly. Canavan registered as a member of the Killyclogher [[hurling]] club, even though he didn't play the sport, just so he would be eligible for selection for the Tyrone [[List of Gaelic games terminology#M|minors]]. Prior to that, he had not played legitimate club football, but had forged his way onto the Tyrone under-age teams with his performances at school level. The two clubs united under the banner of Errigal Ciaran two years later.<ref name=HoganStand>{{cite magazine |url= http://hoganstand.com/Tyrone/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=50132 |title= Canavan biography in Hogan Stand magazine |accessdate=25 January 2007 | date = 8 November 1991 | magazine = [[Hogan Stand]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Canavan won the [[All-Ireland Minor Football Championship|Ulster minor Championship]], an under eighteens tournament, but lost in the All-Ireland semi-final to [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]]. The crux of this team, including [[Adrian Cush]], [[Ciaran Corr]] and others, would stay together as part of the senior team for most of the nineties.\nCanavan captained Tyrone to two [[All-Ireland Under-21 Football Championship]]s titles in 1991 and 1992, having been on the team which lost the 1990 final, again to Kerry.<ref name=program>{{Cite journal | publisher = DBA Publishing | date = 25 September 2005 | journal = 2005 All-Ireland Final Match Programme | title= Player Profiles \u2013 Tyrone | postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref> In four years as an Under 21 player, Canavan scored 13\u201353 (13 goals and 53 points\u2014each goal equals 3 points; 13&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;3 + 53 = 92 points, see [[Gaelic football#Scoring|GAA scoring rules]]) for Tyrone.<ref name=\"TeamTalk\">{{cite journal |title=Will this All-Ireland be the last chapter in the Canavan story? |journal=Team Talk |first=Kenny |last=Curran |issue=45 |pages=14\u201319 |date=September 2005 |publisher= All-Star Publications, Ltd.}}</ref> By the time he was twenty, he was already an automatic choice in the senior panel.\n\n==Early senior career: 1993\u20131998==\nCanavan's name was already known around Tyrone because of his exploits for the Under 21 team,<ref name=PeterBio /> but he started to make an impact in the [[Ulster Senior Football Championship]] in [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship 1994|1994]], as Tyrone lost to eventual All-Ireland champions, [[Down GAA|Down]]. He was the top scorer in the province,<ref name=UlsterScorers /> earning him his first [[GAA All Stars Awards|All Star]], at the age of 23.<ref name=\"AllStars\">{{cite magazine | url= http://www.hoganstand.com/allstars/football.aspx | title= Football All Stars | accessdate= 25 January 2007 | magazine= [[Hogan Stand]] | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060204175138/http://www.hoganstand.com/allstars/football.aspx | archivedate= 4 February 2006 | df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===1995 All-Ireland Final===\n{{main|1995 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final}}\nThroughout the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship 1995|1995 championship]], Canavan had spearheaded Tyrone's march to the final, with round after round of massive scoring exploits. Against [[Derry GAA|Derry]] in the Ulster Semi-final, he scored 0\u20138, and against [[Galway GAA|Galway]] in the All-Ireland semi-final, he scored 1\u20137.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culturenorthernireland.org/article.aspx?county=0&articleID=1304&cultID=0&townID=0&cultSubID=0&page=0&navID=0 |title=The Artful Manager |accessdate=10 May 2007 |date=14 April 2006 |publisher=Culture Northern Ireland |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930181803/http://www.culturenorthernireland.org/article.aspx?county=0&articleID=1304&cultID=0&townID=0&cultSubID=0&page=0&navID=0 |archivedate=30 September 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nTyrone reached their second All-Ireland Final in 1995, and were up against [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] who hadn't won a Championship since the 1980s. In a turgid match, Canavan scored eleven of Tyrone's twelve points in the, but still ended up on the losing side. The game was remembered as contentious for Tyrone fans, for the fact that a point that would have equalised the match in the dying seconds was controversially disallowed, because the blind-sided referee deemed Canavan to have touched the ball on the ground.<ref name= Eyesore/> The referee, Paddy Russell stated in his autobiography that he was certain the ball was on the ground, but Canavan contested in the same book that he managed to get elevation on the ball as he punched, which would have been very difficult to do if it was touching the ground.<ref name=\"Russell\">{{cite book |title=Final Whistle |last=Russell |first= Paddy |authorlink= |author2=Jackie Cahill|year= 2008|publisher= Mainstream Publishing|location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-1-84596-391-0}}</ref> \nHe was the top scorer in Ireland that year, with a total of 1\u201338,<ref name=\"TeamTalk\" /> earning him the inaugural [[All Stars Footballer of the Year|Footballer of the Year]] title.<ref name=\"AllStars\" /> The fact that Canavan's scoring tally was so far ahead of his peers on the team led to suggestions that Tyrone were depending too heavily on him.<ref name=Eyesore />\n\n===1996: Injury===\nFor the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship 1996|1996 championship]], Canavan was handed the captaincy of Tyrone, and was Ulster's leading scorer for the third year in a row,<ref name=UlsterScorers /> and subsequently awarded his third successive All Star.<ref name=\"AllStars\" /> Tyrone reached the All-Ireland semi-final against [[Meath GAA|Meath]], but Canavan was one of six Tyrone players to sustain injuries that day, which some Tyrone fans attribute to Meath's heavy-handedness.<ref>{{cite news | newspaper = [[Irish Independent]] | url = http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/return-of-the-royals-1051891.html | author = Martin Breheny | title = Return of the Royals | date = 4 August 2007 | accessdate = 29 January 2009 | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref> Canavan's injury was so severe that he was still feeling the effects for over a year,<ref name=PeterBio /> and there was speculation as to whether he had been playing on a broken foot.<ref name=SligoPreview>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/2140983.stm | title= Tyrone can maintain progress | accessdate= 25 January 2007 | work = [[BBC Sport]] | date = 21 July 2002 }}</ref>\n\n==1998\u20132000: International stage==\nDuring a weak period for Tyrone Seniors in the late 1990s, Canavan represented [[Ireland international rules football team|Ireland]] in the inaugural [[International Rules Series]] in 1998 against [[Australian international rules football team|Australia]]. In 1999, he was named vice-captain of the team for the tour to Australia, and Ireland came away convincing winners, with Canavan scoring eleven points in the first test in [[Adelaide]], South Australia.<ref name=interRules>{{cite magazine | url= http://www.hoganstand.com/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=36171 | title= Ireland are go! |accessdate=25 January 2007 | magazine = [[Hogan Stand]] | date = 30 October 1999}}</ref> In 2000, <!-- Canavan was left off the initial squad, and instead put on the stand-by list. However, the drawn All-Ireland final that year meant that six players would be unavailable for the tour. The replay was only a day before the first test, so all the players on standby were called up.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/942757.stm | title= Canavan set for Ireland recall |accessdate=22 February 2007 | work = [[BBC Sport]] | date = 20 September 2000}}</ref> --> In the first test Australia's [[Jason Akermanis]] gave Canavan a bloody nose 20 seconds into the game.<ref name=Jason>{{cite news |first=Alan |last=Rodgers |title=Five moments that define Peter the Great |url= |work=Gaelic Life |publisher= |date=17 October 2008 |pages=21 }}</ref> Canavan was sent off in the second test, after fighting with Akermanis. He was banned for one match, which wouldn't be played until the next year, so he ruled himself out of the next series.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/low/northern_ireland/1530897.stm | title= Canavan out of Rules series| accessdate=22 February 2007 | work = [[BBC Sport]] | date = 7 September 2001 }}</ref>\nIn five tests Canavan scored 37 points, becoming one of the few Irish players to leave their mark on the Australian supporters.<ref name=WorldFootyNews>{{cite web| url= http://www.worldfootynews.com/article.php?story=20051227222151959 |title= GAA debates International Rules, AFL recruiting, and own international dimension | accessdate=23 April 2007 | author = 'Peter P' | publisher = World Footy News | date = 7 January 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Late senior career==\nTyrone were one of the favourites for the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship 2002|2002 All-Ireland]], having won their first [[National Football League (Ireland)|National Football League]] in the spring,<ref name=SligoPreview /> but ended up losing a qualifying match to [[Sligo GAA|Sligo]], even though Canavan scored six points on the day.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/2142637.stm | title = Tyrone stunned by Sligo | work = BBC Sport | date = 21 July 2002| postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> That particular defeat stunned him so much, he considered retiring Inter County football.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/3150230.stm | title = Tyrone win predicted in 1997 | work = [[BBC Sport]] | date = 2 October 2003 | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref>\nDespite that, he won his fourth All Star that year, the only Tyrone player to do so,<ref name=\"AllStars\" /> which made him Tyrone's most represented player on the All Star Roll of Honour, overtaking [[Eugene McKenna]], his manager at the time.<ref>{{cite magazine | url = http://www.hoganstand.com/Tyrone/Profile.aspx | title = Tyrone Profile | accessdate = 17 May 2007 | magazine = Hogan Stand | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130410015247/http://www.hoganstand.com/Tyrone/Profile.aspx | archive-date = 10 April 2013 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===2003: Championship glory===\nIn 2003, Canavan shook off his tag as 'the greatest player never to win an All-Ireland',<ref name=UUJ /><ref>{{cite news | newspaper = [[Daily Mirror]] | date = 26 September 2003 | author = Orla Bannon | title = GAA: Praying for Saint Peter | postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref> captaining Tyrone to their first [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]]. As he approached the podium on [[Croke Park]]'s Hogan Stand after the final, his nervousness was visible, and after being handed the trophy, he made an emotional speech about how he had to enviously watch other Ulster teams lift the [[Sam Maguire Cup]], but \"to eventually win it is something else.\"<ref name = BBCfinal2003>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/low/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/3147218.stm | title= Tyrone are All-Ireland champions | accessdate = 17 May 2007 | work =[[BBC Sport]] | date = 28 September 2003 | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref>\n\nHis appearance in the final was remarkable for the fact that he was the top scorer of the day with five points,<ref name=Indo /> despite having suffered an ankle injury in the previous match, and was not expected (or advised) to play.<ref name=PeterBio /> He started the final and was taken off before half time. During the break, and even some way into the second half, he was receiving treatment to his ankle, including pain-killing injections.\n<br/>With ten minutes remaining, he was reintroduced by manager [[Mickey Harte]],<ref name = BBCfinal2003 /> likely due to his experience as the only member of the team who had played in an All-Ireland final before. This reintroduction, while not the first time it had happened (blood substitutions had been used sporadically, for example), was seen as one of the greatest moments in the GAA in the last forty years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/tv/gaamoments/20moments.html |title=Wayback Machine cache of RT\u00c9 Sport's announcements of the nominees |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050422020916/http://www.rte.ie/tv/gaamoments/20moments.html |archivedate=22 April 2005 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn the drawn Ulster final against Down, Canavan was playing a week after the death of his father. He remarked in his autobiography that he feared Tyrone were going to lose by one of the biggest margins in Ulster Championship history, if they didn't stem the flow of the Down attack.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/3063021.stm | title= Clones thriller ends in draw |accessdate= 25 January 2007 | date = 13 July 2003 | work = [[BBC Sport]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | first=Peter | last=Canavan | title=Every Step We Took. 2003 \u2013 Football Odyssey | publisher=All Star Print Ltd. | location= Omagh, Northern Ireland | year=2004 | isbn=0-9546616-0-5 | page = 48}}</ref> When Tyrone were awarded a penalty, Canavan stepped up, due to [[Stephen O'Neill]] (the first choice penalty-taker) being on the bench. He took the kick, and managed to find the net, later describing it as \"the most important [kick] of my career,\" citing the fact that if Tyrone had been heavily beaten, they probably wouldn't have been able to pick themselves up to play in the 'back door' qualifier series.<ref>{{cite book | first=Peter | last=Canavan | title=Every Step We Took. 2003 \u2013 Football Odyssey | publisher=All Star Print Ltd. | location=Omagh, Northern Ireland | year=2004 | isbn=0-9546616-0-5 | page = 51}}</ref>\n\nOver the course of the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship 2003|2003 Championship]], he amassed a total of 1\u201348 (a total of 51 points),<ref name=Indo>{{cite news| url= http://www.unison.ie/irish_independent/stories.php3?ca=95&si=1111318&issue_id=10328 | title=Captain fantastic Canavan scoops readers' top award | accessdate= 29 April 2007 | newspaper = [[Irish Independent]] | date = 20 January 2004| postscript= <!--None-->}}</ref> and had won the National League in the spring, all of which earned him a fifth All Star.<ref name=\"AllStars\" /> Among his more notable performances of the year included an eight-point haul in the replayed first round match against [[Derry GAA|Derry]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/2003/0524/tyrone.html |title=Tyrone destroy dismal Derry |accessdate=4 March 2007 |date=24 May 2003 |publisher=[[RT\u00c9]] Sport |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605114150/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/2003/0524/tyrone.html |archivedate=5 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> and in the replayed Ulster Final, Canavan scored eleven points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/2003/0720/tyrone.html |title=Disappointing Down no match for silky Tyrone |accessdate=4 March 2007 |publisher=[[RT\u00c9]] Sport |date=20 July 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605114204/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/2003/0720/tyrone.html |archivedate=5 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nHe became the first GAA star to gain an honorary doctorate from the [[University of Ulster]],<ref name=UUJ /> and was also voted [[BBC Northern Ireland Sports Personality of the Year]],<ref>{{cite news| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/low/northern_ireland/3297059.stm | title=Canavan wins BBC award| accessdate=25 January 2007 | date = 6 December 2003 | publisher= [[BBC Sport]] | work=BBC News}}</ref> a regional award of the [[BBC Sports Personality of the Year]]. Following an email campaign throughout Ireland, Canavan was an early forerunner for the national award, despite the fact that Gaelic games have very little exposure in Great Britain.<ref name=buzzle>{{cite web|url=http://www.buzzle.com/editorials/12-9-2003-48440.asp |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130118181216/http://www.buzzle.com/editorials/12-9-2003-48440.asp |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 January 2013 |title=Whole of Ireland Behind Peter Canavan's BBC Sports Personality of the Year Campaign |accessdate=25 January 2007 |date=10 December 2003 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2003 final, Canavan relinquished the captaincy to [[Cormac McAnallen]], but the 24-year-old died shortly after taking up the position. This tragedy adversely affected the mindset of the team, and they were unable to defend their All-Ireland.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/4130065.stm | work=BBC News | title=McAnallen death overshadows year | date=28 December 2004 | accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2005: Championship swan song===\nCanavan was used mostly as an 'impact substitute' throughout the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship 2005|2005 Championship]]\u2014brought on to either unsettle the opposition, or rally his teammates.<ref name=PeterBio /> This backfired when he was controversially sent off within a minute of coming on as a substitute in the [[Ulster Senior Football Championship|Ulster Final replay]] replay.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.rte.ie/sport/2005/0723/armagh.html | title=Armagh take Ulster title in scrappy affair|accessdate=4 March 2007 | publisher = [[RT\u00c9]] Sport | date = 23 July 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn the All-Ireland semi-final against [[Armagh GAA|Armagh]] (who were meeting Tyrone for the third time that year), Canavan scored with the last kick of the game, winning the match for Tyrone.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/low/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/4213594.stm | title= Armagh 1\u201312 1\u201313 Tyrone ALL-IRELAND SEMI-fINAL| accessdate=25 January 2007 | date = 4 September 2005 | work = [[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> Kevin McStay, a former [[Mayo GAA|Mayo]] player, described it as the point of the season, despite the free kick being from a relatively straightforward position.<ref>{{cite magazine| url= http://www.hoganstand.com/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=54858 | title=Kevin McStay Column | date= 21 December 2005| accessdate=2 April 2007 | magazine =[[Hogan Stand]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Canavan 2005 final goal.jpg|thumb|150px | left | Canavan (13, white) drilling home Tyrone's winning goal in the 2005 All-Ireland final]] Mickey Harte chose Canavan on the starting line-up of the All-Ireland final and went on to score Tyrone's only goal, winning on a scoreline of 1\u201316 to 2\u201310.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/4281008.stm | title= Tyrone triumph in Croker decider|accessdate=25 January 2007 | work = [[BBC Sport]] | date =25 September 2005}}</ref>\n\nHe retired from inter-county football following this performance with a sixth All Star, ending a sixteen-year tenure in Senior championship football.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/4284812.stm |title= Lawn joins Canavan in retirement | accessdate=25 January 2007 | date = 26 September 2005| work = [[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> He said of his decision, \"I have spent enough time on the treatment table\", referring to the instances where he played while carrying potentially career-threatening injuries, as he had done in 1996 and 2003. Canavan's appearance in the 2005 final (his last game for Tyrone), was his forty-ninth Championship match.\n\n==Other intercounty successes==\nCanavan was part of both Tyrone sides that won the [[National Football League (Ireland)|National Football League]] title two years in a row\u2014in 2002 and 2003<ref name=PeterBio />\u2014and he competed in the 1994 final against Derry. His success in other competitions include five [[Railway Cup]]s, two Vocational Schools titles, and one [[Dr. McKenna Cup]].<ref name=TeamTalk />\n\n==Club career==\nAfter retiring from inter-county football, he continued to play at club level for [[Errigal Ciar\u00e1n]] until 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thespiritofpaulmcgirr.com/content/view/58/2/ |title=Canavan Runs for the Spirit of Paul McGirr |accessdate=20 October 2008 |work=The Spirit of Paul McGirr website |year=2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106123316/http://thespiritofpaulmcgirr.com/content/view/58/2/ |archivedate=6 January 2009 }}</ref> During the seventeen years he played he won six [[Tyrone Senior Club Football Championship|Tyrone Senior Club]] titles and two [[Ulster Senior Club Football Championship|Ulster Club Championships]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.errigalciaran.com/club_achievements.asp |title=Errigal Ciaran achievements |accessdate=25 January 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070421135052/http://www.errigalciaran.com/club_achievements.asp |archivedate=21 April 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref> and in 2006, he won his first Tyrone All Star for his performances in the club championship.<ref>{{cite magazine |url= http://www.hoganstand.com/Tyrone/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=70439 | title=Canavan wins first Tyrone All-Star | accessdate=25 January 2007 | date = 20 December 2006 | magazine = [[Hogan Stand]] }}</ref>\nIn December 2008, he moved into management for the first time, by taking charge of Errigal Ciaran,<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2008/1229/1229728618500.html |title=Canavan to manage Errigal | accessdate = 29 December 2008 | date = 29 December 2008 | newspaper = [[The Irish Times]] | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref> leading them to win the Tyrone All County League final in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nwipp-newspapers.com/SC/free/295869823020783.php |newspaper=Ulster Herald |date=12 November 2009 |author=Kevin Kelly |title=Final flourish sees Errigal home }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Disciplinary problems==\nHis career features many examples of indiscipline,<ref>{{Cite news | last =Keys | first =Colm | title = Tyrone ace Canavan's jaw broken | newspaper = [[Daily Mirror|The Mirror]] | pages = 36 | date= 30 April 1998 | postscript =<!--None-->}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/bbc_pundits/1564155.stm | work= [[BBC Sport]] | author = Jerome Quinn | title = Jerome Quinn: My End of Season Awards | date = 26 September 2001 | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref> including on-pitch scuffles with other players.<ref name=Jason /> which at times threatened to overshadow his achievements. [[Jack O'Connor (Gaelic footballer)|Jack O'Connor]], [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]]'s manager in the 2005 All-Ireland final, suggested in his autobiography that Canavan tackled [[Colm Cooper]] off the ball, preventing him getting into a goal-scoring position,<ref>{{cite book\n  | last =O'Connor\n  | first =Jack\n  | authorlink = Jack O'Connor (Gaelic footballer)\n  | title =Keys to the Kingdom\n  | publisher =Penguin Ireland\n  | date= 4 July 2007\n  | isbn = 1-84488-153-9}}</ref> a claim backed up by ''[[Sunday Tribune]]'' journalist, Kieran Shannon.<ref>{{Cite news\n |last=Shannon \n |first=Keiran \n |title=A history of violence \n |newspaper=[[Sunday Tribune]] \n |pages= \n |date=12 February 2006 \n |url=http://www.tribune.ie/archive/article/2006/feb/12/a-history-of-violence/\n |format= \n |postscript= \n}}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Management career==\nCanavan was appointed manager of [[Fermanagh GAA|Fermanagh]] in November 2011 on a three-year term to be reviewed annually, with trainer Kieran Donnelly and selector Enda Kilpatrick joining him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2011/1121/canavanp_fermanagh.html |title=Canavan appointed Fermanagh manager |publisher=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |accessdate=21 November 2011 |date=21 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123123335/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2011/1121/canavanp_fermanagh.html |archivedate=23 November 2011 }}</ref> His first game against Antrim, saw Fermanagh winning by a scoreline of 2 \u2013 11 to 1 \u2013 06.\n\nHe stepped down as Fermanagh manager in September 2013.<ref>{{cite news|first=Colm|last=Keys|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/peter-canavan-decides-to-opt-out-after-two-years-as-fermanagh-manager-29546596.html|title=Peter Canavan decides to opt out after two years as Fermanagh manager|newspaper=Irish Independent|publisher=Independent News & Media|date=3 September 2013|accessdate=3 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nHowever, Canavan was not out of management for long. He was appointed manager of [[Cavan Gaels GAA|Cavan Gaels]] in December 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the42.ie/peter-canavan-ratified-new-manager-cavan-gaels-1218616-Dec2013/|title=Peter Canavan ratified as new manager of Cavan Gaels|work=The42||date=12 December 2013|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref> He guided them to their 1st [[Cavan Senior Football Championship|Senior Championship]] in 3 years in October 2014, defeating [[Kingscourt Stars GAA|Kingscourt Stars]] in the final by a point.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-games/gaelic-football/lyng-seals-the-deal-to-leave-kingscourt-seeing-stars-30658440.html|title=Lyng seals the deal to leave Kingscourt seeing stars|work=Independent||date=12 October 2014|accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref> This was seen as a huge success for Canavan and the Cavan Gaels Club.\n\nAfter delivering the Oliver Plunkett trophy back to the Cavan town club, he then went on to become a selector with the Tyrone under 21 panel in 2015. He was part of the management team which consisted of Fergal Logan (Manager) and Brian Dooher. They guided the under 21s to an Ulster Final victory against Donegal in Celtic Park, and subsequently, to the All Ireland title, defeating Tipperary in the final.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.hoganstand.com/Tyrone/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=50132 Hoganstand GAA Immortals]\n* [http://www.tyronegaa.ie/ Official Tyrone Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060526102917/http://www.gaelsport.com/html/club/club_home.jsp?c=586 Errigal Ciar\u00e1n Official Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070930165132/http://www.culturenorthernireland.org/article.aspx?co=14&ca=15&to=0&sca=0&articleID=641&navID=10 Culture Northern Ireland Biography]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports|gaa}}\n{{succession box\n | before=First year awarded\n | title=[[All Stars Footballer of the Year]]\n | years=1995\n | after=[[Martin O'Connell (footballer)|Martin O'Connell]]<br/>([[Meath GAA|Meath]])\n}}\n{{succession box\n | before=[[Kieran McGeeney]]<br/>([[Armagh GAA|Armagh]])\n | title=[[List of All-Ireland Senior Football Championship winning captains|All-Ireland Senior Football]]<br/>winning [[Captain (sport)|captain]]\n | years=2003\n | after=[[Dara \u00d3 Cinn\u00e9ide]]<br/>([[Kerry GAA|Kerry]])\n}}\n{{succession box\n | before=[[Kieran McGeeney]]<br/>([[Armagh GAA|Armagh]])\n | title=[[Texaco Footballer of the Year]]\n | years=2003\n | after=[[Colm Cooper]]<br/>([[Kerry GAA|Kerry]])\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Navboxes colour\n|title=Tyrone Football Squads\n|bg=white\n|fg=red\n|list1=\n{{Tyrone Football Team 1995}}\n{{Tyrone Football Team 2003}}\n{{Tyrone Football Team 2005}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title=Awards\n|titlestyle=background: gold\n|list1=\n{{1994 All Stars}}\n{{1995 All Stars}}\n{{1996 All Stars}}\n{{2002 All Stars}}\n{{2003 All Stars}}\n{{2005 All Stars}}\n{{All Stars Footballer of the Year}}\n{{BBC Northern Ireland Sports Personality of the Year winners}}\n{{1st Irish News Ulster All Stars}}\n{{2nd Irish News Ulster All Stars}}\n{{8th Irish News Ulster All Stars}}\n{{Irish News Ulster All Stars Team of the Decade}}\n{{Texaco Footballer of the Year}}\n}}\n{{Fermanagh Gaelic football team managers}}\n\n{{good article}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Canavan, Peter}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:All-Ireland-winning captains (football)]]\n[[Category:All Stars Gaelic Footballer of the Year]]\n[[Category:Errigal Ciar\u00e1n Gaelic footballers]]\n[[Category:Gaelic football forwards]]\n[[Category:Gaelic football managers]]\n[[Category:Irish international rules football players]]\n[[Category:Irish schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:Texaco Footballers of the Year]]\n[[Category:Tyrone inter-county Gaelic footballers]]\n[[Category:Winners of two All-Ireland medals (Gaelic football)]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the Garda officer|Peter P. Canavan}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=May 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2015}}\n{{Infobox Gaelic Athletic Association player\n|image             = Peter Canavan - SFC 2005 cc 3.0.jpg\n|caption           = Canavan lifting the [[Sam Maguire Cup]] in 2003\n|name              = Peter Canavan\n|irish             = Peadar \u00d3 Ceannabh\u00e1in\n|nickname          = Peter 'The Great',<ref>{{Cite news|last=O'Sullivan |first=Jim |title=Peter the Great ready to answer Tyrone's call |date=19 June 2004 |newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]] |url=http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2004/06/19/story757189885.asp |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070929145520/http://archives.tcm.ie/irishexaminer/2004/06/19/story757189885.asp |archivedate=29 September 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref name=SundayTimes /><br/>'Petrol Pete'\n| feet             = 5\n| inches           = 9\n|occupation        = Teacher<ref name=program />\n|sport             = Gaelic football\n|code              = Football\n|county            = Tyrone\n|province          = Ulster\n|clposition        = Forward\n|club              = Errigal Ciaran \n|clyears           = 1990\u20132007\n|clapps(points)    = \n|clcounty          = 6\n|clprovince        = 2\n|clubs             = [[Errigal Ciar\u00e1n GAC]]\n|counties          = Tyrone\n|icposition        = Forward\n|icyears           = 1989\u20132005\n|icapps(points)    = 49 (9\u2013191 (218))<ref name= UlsterScorers />\n|icprovince        = 5\n|icallireland      = 2\n|allstars          = 6\n|nfl               = 2\n|icupdate          = (22:03, 21 December 2006 (UTC))<ref name=\"TeamTalk\" />\n|clupdate          = (15:04, 10 January 2007 (UTC)))<ref name=\"TeamTalk\" />\n|birth_date        = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1971|04|09}}\n|birth_place       = Ballygawley, [[County Tyrone]], Northern Ireland\n}}\n'''Peter Canavan''' (born 9 April 1971) is a former [[Irish people|Irish]] [[Gaelic football]] player, [[Manager (Gaelic games)|manager]] and pundit  for Tyrone.\n\nHe played inter-county football for [[Tyrone GAA|Tyrone]], and is one of the most decorated players in the game's history, winning two [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]] medals, six [[List of All Stars Awards winners (football)|All Stars Awards]] (more than any other Ulster player, and joint third overall),<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.unison.ie/irish_independent/stories.php3?ca=37&si=1514357&issue_id=13331 | title = Big three sweep awards boards | accessdate=25 January 2007 | date=26 November 2005 | author = Martin Breheny | publisher= [[Irish Independent]] Online}}</ref> four [[Ulster Senior Football Championship|provincial titles]], and two [[National Football League (Ireland)|National Leagues]] and several under-age and club championship medals. He represented [[Ireland international rules football team|Ireland]] in the [[International Rules Series]] on several occasions from 1998 until 2000.<ref name=interRules/> He is considered one of the great players of the last twenty years by commentators such as John Haughey of the [[BBC]],<ref name=PeterBio>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/4284352.stm | title= Canavan's remarkable career| accessdate= 25 January 2007 | author = John Haughey| work = [[BBC Sport]] | date = 26 September 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.anfearrua.com/ViewSectionDetail.asp?docid=1235 |title= Two Bald Eagles: Peter The Great and Lion Hearted Leo |accessdate= 25 January 2007 |date= 3 October 2003 |author= 'Press Box Lad' |publisher= An Fear Rua |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070406040900/http://www.anfearrua.com/ViewSectionDetail.asp?docid=1235 |archive-date= 6 April 2007 |url-status= dead }}</ref> and in 2009, he was named in the ''[[Sunday Tribune]]''{{'}}s list of the ''125 Most Influential People in GAA History''.<ref name=\"125 tribune\">{{cite news |first=Enda |last=McEvoy |author2=Kieran Shannon, Dave Hannigan (and PJ Cunningham, Malachy Clerkin and Pat Nugent) |title=125 Most Influential People in GAA History |work=[[Sunday Tribune]] |date=4 January 2009 |accessdate=20 January 2009 |url=http://www.tribune.ie/article/2009/jan/04/125-most-influential-people-in-gaa-history-125-101 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090809014716/http://www.tribune.ie/article/2009/jan/04/125-most-influential-people-in-gaa-history-125-101 |archivedate=9 August 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nHis scoring record of 218 points is the second highest of all time in the [[Ulster Senior Football Championship]].<ref name=UlsterScorers>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/low/northern_ireland/the_championship/5192032.stm |title= Ulster's hot-shots |accessdate=25 January 2007 | date=18 July 2006 | work = [[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> His early high scoring rate, when he would often be Tyrone's best performer<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/2011209.stm |title= Peter's loss lamented| accessdate= 29 April 2007 | author = Jerome Quinn | date = 27 May 2002 | work=BBC News}}</ref> \u2013 particularly in the [[1995 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final]] when he scored eleven of Tyrone's twelve points\u2014led to claims that Tyrone was a \"one-man show,\" and that the team was too dependent on him, particularly in his early career.<ref name=Eyesore >{{cite news | url= http://www.unison.ie/irish_independent/stories.php3?ca=95&si=1446552&issue_id=12836 | title = Tyrone and Canavan came up short in 'eyesore' final| accessdate= 25 January 2007 | newspaper = [[Irish Independent]] | date = 7 August 2005 | author = Sean Ryan}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | title = Gormley chases double with help from Canavan | newspaper = [[The Belfast Telegraph]] | date= 24 June 1996 | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref><ref name=\"GL_17/10/08\">{{cite news |first=Alan |last=Rodgers |title=Candid Canavan |url= |work=Gaelic Life |publisher= |date=17 October 2008 |pages=20\u201321 }}</ref>\n\nSince retiring as a player he has managed the [[Fermanagh GAA|Fermanagh]] inter-county Gaelic football team (2011\u20132013).\n\n==Personal life==\nCanavan is from Glencull, near [[Ballygawley, County Tyrone|Ballygawley]], County Tyrone<ref name=\"GL_17/10/08\"/> and was the tenth of eleven children.<ref name=SundayTimes>{{Cite news | last =Walsh | first =David | title = Gaelic games | newspaper = [[The Sunday Times]] | date = 28 August 1996 | postscript =<!--None-->}}</ref> His older brother, [[Pascal Canavan|Pascal]], played with him on the Tyrone panel for most of the 1990s. He is married to Finola (sister of former Tyrone team-mate Ronan McGarrity<ref name=\"GL_17/10/08\"/>), and has four children, Aine, Claire, Darragh and Ruairi, and has been a Physical Education teacher in Holy Trinity College, [[Cookstown, County Tyrone|Cookstown]], throughout most of his career (Gaelic games are amateur sports).<ref name=\"GL_17/10/08\"/><ref name=UUJ>{{cite web|url=http://news.ulster.ac.uk/releases/2003/955.html |title=University To Honour Ulster Sporting Heroes Canavan And Humphreys |accessdate=25 January 2007 |date=30 October 2003 |publisher=[[University of Ulster]] |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303183420/http://news.ulster.ac.uk/releases/2003/955.html |archivedate=3 March 2016 }}</ref> While there, he taught [[Eoin Mulligan]] his point-taking technique, and the pair have been known in the media as 'master and student' ever since, particularly by television commentators.<ref>{{cite news| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sportacademy/hi/sa/special_events/gaelic_sports/newsid_3135000/3135296.stm | title =Learning at school| accessdate=2 May 2007 | work = [[BBC Sport]] | date=24 September 2003}}</ref>\n\nHe writes a column for the [[Gaelic games]] magazine, ''[[Hogan Stand]]''<ref>{{cite magazine | url= http://www.hoganstand.com/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=46266 | title= Canavan's Hogan Stand column regarding the decision by the GAA to abolish Rule 42 |accessdate= 25 January 2007 | date = 10 May 2005 | magazine = [[Hogan Stand]]}}</ref> and the Northern Ireland edition of ''[[The Daily Mirror]]''.<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/northernireland/2006/11/03/football-when-geezer-exploded-it-shook-us-up-89520-18037987/ | title = When Geezer exploded it shook us up | author = Peter Canavan | accessdate = 26 August 2007 | newspaper = [[The Daily Mirror]] | postscript= <!--None-->}} {{Dead link|date=April 2012|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> and in 2008, Canavan joined [[TV3 (Ireland)|TV3]] as a football pundit for their first year of broadcasting live GAA matches.<ref>{{Cite journal | url = http://www.tv3.ie/pr_sub.php?type=1&view_pr=55 | title = TV3 Announce GAA line up for the 2009 Championship season | publisher = [[TV3 (Ireland)]] | author = TV3 press release | date = 26 May 2009 | accessdate = 15 January 2010 | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref>\n\nIn 2003, just over a week before Tyrone's Ulster final appearance against [[Down GAA|Down]], Canavan's father, Se\u00e1n, died. It came as a shock to Canavan, who had thought his father (who was already in hospital) was getting better. He decided to play in the match, stating that he knew, subconsciously \"[he] was going to be playing in the Ulster final all along and Daddy certainly wouldn't have wanted [him] to do anything but play.\"<ref>{{cite book | first=Peter | last=Canavan | title=Every Step We Took. 2003 \u2013 A Football Odyssey | publisher=All Star Print Ltd. | location=Omagh, Northern Ireland | year=2004 | isbn=0-9546616-0-5 | page = 46}}</ref>\n\nCanavan has suffered from [[asthma]] since he was a child, and has battled throughout his career to control the ailment. He told the Asthma Society of Ireland, \"I thought to myself, this is something that I am just going to have to put up with.\" In later years, however, improved medication has afforded Canavan what he described as, \"a better quality of life\".<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.irishhealth.com/clin/asthma/canavan.html |title=Peter Canavan \u2013 Life With Asthma |accessdate=25 January 2007 | publisher = irishhealth.com}}</ref>\n\n==Under-age career==\nTo play for an [[GAA county|inter-county GAA team]], Canavan had to work around a [[Gaelic Athletic Association]] (GAA) bylaw, because of a dispute in his parish, [[Errigal Ciar\u00e1n]]. Two clubs claimed to represent the parish, the established Ballygawley St. Ciaran's club and the newly formed club, then called Errigal Ciaran Naomh Malachai. Players from the Errigal team were not recognised as being GAA members, because the club failed to register correctly. Canavan registered as a member of the Killyclogher [[hurling]] club, even though he didn't play the sport, just so he would be eligible for selection for the Tyrone [[List of Gaelic games terminology#M|minors]]. Prior to that, he had not played legitimate club football, but had forged his way onto the Tyrone under-age teams with his performances at school level. The two clubs united under the banner of Errigal Ciaran two years later.<ref name=HoganStand>{{cite magazine |url= http://hoganstand.com/Tyrone/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=50132 |title= Canavan biography in Hogan Stand magazine |accessdate=25 January 2007 | date = 8 November 1991 | magazine = [[Hogan Stand]]}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Canavan won the [[All-Ireland Minor Football Championship|Ulster minor Championship]], an under eighteens tournament, but lost in the All-Ireland semi-final to [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]]. The crux of this team, including [[Adrian Cush]], [[Ciaran Corr]] and others, would stay together as part of the senior team for most of the nineties.\nCanavan captained Tyrone to two [[All-Ireland Under-21 Football Championship]]s titles in 1991 and 1992, having been on the team which lost the 1990 final, again to Kerry.<ref name=program>{{Cite journal | publisher = DBA Publishing | date = 25 September 2005 | journal = 2005 All-Ireland Final Match Programme | title= Player Profiles \u2013 Tyrone | postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref> In four years as an Under 21 player, Canavan scored 13\u201353 (13 goals and 53 points\u2014each goal equals 3 points; 13&nbsp;\u00d7&nbsp;3 + 53 = 92 points, see [[Gaelic football#Scoring|GAA scoring rules]]) for Tyrone.<ref name=\"TeamTalk\">{{cite journal |title=Will this All-Ireland be the last chapter in the Canavan story? |journal=Team Talk |first=Kenny |last=Curran |issue=45 |pages=14\u201319 |date=September 2005 |publisher= All-Star Publications, Ltd.}}</ref> By the time he was twenty, he was already an automatic choice in the senior panel.\n\n==Early senior career: 1993\u20131998==\nCanavan's name was already known around Tyrone because of his exploits for the Under 21 team,<ref name=PeterBio /> but he started to make an impact in the [[Ulster Senior Football Championship]] in [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship 1994|1994]], as Tyrone lost to eventual All-Ireland champions, [[Down GAA|Down]]. He was the top scorer in the province,<ref name=UlsterScorers /> earning him his first [[GAA All Stars Awards|All Star]], at the age of 23.<ref name=\"AllStars\">{{cite magazine | url= http://www.hoganstand.com/allstars/football.aspx | title= Football All Stars | accessdate= 25 January 2007 | magazine= [[Hogan Stand]] | url-status= dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060204175138/http://www.hoganstand.com/allstars/football.aspx | archivedate= 4 February 2006 | df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===1995 All-Ireland Final===\n{{main|1995 All-Ireland Senior Football Championship Final}}\nThroughout the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship 1995|1995 championship]], Canavan had spearheaded Tyrone's march to the final, with round after round of massive scoring exploits. Against [[Derry GAA|Derry]] in the Ulster Semi-final, he scored 0\u20138, and against [[Galway GAA|Galway]] in the All-Ireland semi-final, he scored 1\u20137.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culturenorthernireland.org/article.aspx?county=0&articleID=1304&cultID=0&townID=0&cultSubID=0&page=0&navID=0 |title=The Artful Manager |accessdate=10 May 2007 |date=14 April 2006 |publisher=Culture Northern Ireland |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930181803/http://www.culturenorthernireland.org/article.aspx?county=0&articleID=1304&cultID=0&townID=0&cultSubID=0&page=0&navID=0 |archivedate=30 September 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nTyrone reached their second All-Ireland Final in 1995, and were up against [[Dublin GAA|Dublin]] who hadn't won a Championship since the 1980s. In a turgid match, Canavan scored eleven of Tyrone's twelve points in the, but still ended up on the losing side. The game was remembered as contentious for Tyrone fans, for the fact that a point that would have equalised the match in the dying seconds was controversially disallowed, because the blind-sided referee deemed Canavan to have touched the ball on the ground.<ref name= Eyesore/> The referee, Paddy Russell stated in his autobiography that he was certain the ball was on the ground, but Canavan contested in the same book that he managed to get elevation on the ball as he punched, which would have been very difficult to do if it was touching the ground.<ref name=\"Russell\">{{cite book |title=Final Whistle |last=Russell |first= Paddy |authorlink= |author2=Jackie Cahill|year= 2008|publisher= Mainstream Publishing|location=Edinburgh |isbn=978-1-84596-391-0}}</ref> \nHe was the top scorer in Ireland that year, with a total of 1\u201338,<ref name=\"TeamTalk\" /> earning him the inaugural [[All Stars Footballer of the Year|Footballer of the Year]] title.<ref name=\"AllStars\" /> The fact that Canavan's scoring tally was so far ahead of his peers on the team led to suggestions that Tyrone were depending too heavily on him.<ref name=Eyesore />\n\n===1996: Injury===\nFor the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship 1996|1996 championship]], Canavan was handed the captaincy of Tyrone, and was Ulster's leading scorer for the third year in a row,<ref name=UlsterScorers /> and subsequently awarded his third successive All Star.<ref name=\"AllStars\" /> Tyrone reached the All-Ireland semi-final against [[Meath GAA|Meath]], but Canavan was one of six Tyrone players to sustain injuries that day, which some Tyrone fans attribute to Meath's heavy-handedness.<ref>{{cite news | newspaper = [[Irish Independent]] | url = http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/return-of-the-royals-1051891.html | author = Martin Breheny | title = Return of the Royals | date = 4 August 2007 | accessdate = 29 January 2009 | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref> Canavan's injury was so severe that he was still feeling the effects for over a year,<ref name=PeterBio /> and there was speculation as to whether he had been playing on a broken foot.<ref name=SligoPreview>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/2140983.stm | title= Tyrone can maintain progress | accessdate= 25 January 2007 | work = [[BBC Sport]] | date = 21 July 2002 }}</ref>\n\n==1998\u20132000: International stage==\nDuring a weak period for Tyrone Seniors in the late 1990s, Canavan represented [[Ireland international rules football team|Ireland]] in the inaugural [[International Rules Series]] in 1998 against [[Australian international rules football team|Australia]]. In 1999, he was named vice-captain of the team for the tour to Australia, and Ireland came away convincing winners, with Canavan scoring eleven points in the first test in [[Adelaide]], South Australia.<ref name=interRules>{{cite magazine | url= http://www.hoganstand.com/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=36171 | title= Ireland are go! |accessdate=25 January 2007 | magazine = [[Hogan Stand]] | date = 30 October 1999}}</ref> In 2000, <!-- Canavan was left off the initial squad, and instead put on the stand-by list. However, the drawn All-Ireland final that year meant that six players would be unavailable for the tour. The replay was only a day before the first test, so all the players on standby were called up.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/942757.stm | title= Canavan set for Ireland recall |accessdate=22 February 2007 | work = [[BBC Sport]] | date = 20 September 2000}}</ref> --> In the first test Australia's [[Jason Akermanis]] gave Canavan a bloody nose 20 seconds into the game.<ref name=Jason>{{cite news |first=Alan |last=Rodgers |title=Five moments that define Peter the Great |url= |work=Gaelic Life |publisher= |date=17 October 2008 |pages=21 }}</ref> Canavan was sent off in the second test, after fighting with Akermanis. He was banned for one match, which wouldn't be played until the next year, so he ruled himself out of the next series.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/low/northern_ireland/1530897.stm | title= Canavan out of Rules series| accessdate=22 February 2007 | work = [[BBC Sport]] | date = 7 September 2001 }}</ref>\nIn five tests Canavan scored 37 points, becoming one of the few Irish players to leave their mark on the Australian supporters.<ref name=WorldFootyNews>{{cite web| url= http://www.worldfootynews.com/article.php?story=20051227222151959 |title= GAA debates International Rules, AFL recruiting, and own international dimension | accessdate=23 April 2007 | author = 'Peter P' | publisher = World Footy News | date = 7 January 2006}}</ref>\n\n==Late senior career==\nTyrone were one of the favourites for the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship 2002|2002 All-Ireland]], having won their first [[National Football League (Ireland)|National Football League]] in the spring,<ref name=SligoPreview /> but ended up losing a qualifying match to [[Sligo GAA|Sligo]], even though Canavan scored six points on the day.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/2142637.stm | title = Tyrone stunned by Sligo | work = BBC Sport | date = 21 July 2002| postscript=<!--None-->}}</ref> That particular defeat stunned him so much, he considered retiring Inter County football.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/3150230.stm | title = Tyrone win predicted in 1997 | work = [[BBC Sport]] | date = 2 October 2003 | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref>\nDespite that, he won his fourth All Star that year, the only Tyrone player to do so,<ref name=\"AllStars\" /> which made him Tyrone's most represented player on the All Star Roll of Honour, overtaking [[Eugene McKenna]], his manager at the time.<ref>{{cite magazine | url = http://www.hoganstand.com/Tyrone/Profile.aspx | title = Tyrone Profile | accessdate = 17 May 2007 | magazine = Hogan Stand | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20130410015247/http://www.hoganstand.com/Tyrone/Profile.aspx | archive-date = 10 April 2013 | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===2003: Championship glory===\nIn 2003, Canavan shook off his tag as 'the greatest player never to win an All-Ireland',<ref name=UUJ /><ref>{{cite news | newspaper = [[Daily Mirror]] | date = 26 September 2003 | author = Orla Bannon | title = GAA: Praying for Saint Peter | postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref> captaining Tyrone to their first [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship]]. As he approached the podium on [[Croke Park]]'s Hogan Stand after the final, his nervousness was visible, and after being handed the trophy, he made an emotional speech about how he had to enviously watch other Ulster teams lift the [[Sam Maguire Cup]], but \"to eventually win it is something else.\"<ref name = BBCfinal2003>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/low/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/3147218.stm | title= Tyrone are All-Ireland champions | accessdate = 17 May 2007 | work =[[BBC Sport]] | date = 28 September 2003 | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref>\n\nHis appearance in the final was remarkable for the fact that he was the top scorer of the day with five points,<ref name=Indo /> despite having suffered an ankle injury in the previous match, and was not expected (or advised) to play.<ref name=PeterBio /> He started the final and was taken off before half time. During the break, and even some way into the second half, he was receiving treatment to his ankle, including pain-killing injections.\n<br/>With ten minutes remaining, he was reintroduced by manager [[Mickey Harte]],<ref name = BBCfinal2003 /> likely due to his experience as the only member of the team who had played in an All-Ireland final before. This reintroduction, while not the first time it had happened (blood substitutions had been used sporadically, for example), was seen as one of the greatest moments in the GAA in the last forty years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/tv/gaamoments/20moments.html |title=Wayback Machine cache of RT\u00c9 Sport's announcements of the nominees |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20050422020916/http://www.rte.ie/tv/gaamoments/20moments.html |archivedate=22 April 2005 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nIn the drawn Ulster final against Down, Canavan was playing a week after the death of his father. He remarked in his autobiography that he feared Tyrone were going to lose by one of the biggest margins in Ulster Championship history, if they didn't stem the flow of the Down attack.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/3063021.stm | title= Clones thriller ends in draw |accessdate= 25 January 2007 | date = 13 July 2003 | work = [[BBC Sport]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | first=Peter | last=Canavan | title=Every Step We Took. 2003 \u2013 Football Odyssey | publisher=All Star Print Ltd. | location= Omagh, Northern Ireland | year=2004 | isbn=0-9546616-0-5 | page = 48}}</ref> When Tyrone were awarded a penalty, Canavan stepped up, due to [[Stephen O'Neill]] (the first choice penalty-taker) being on the bench. He took the kick, and managed to find the net, later describing it as \"the most important [kick] of my career,\" citing the fact that if Tyrone had been heavily beaten, they probably wouldn't have been able to pick themselves up to play in the 'back door' qualifier series.<ref>{{cite book | first=Peter | last=Canavan | title=Every Step We Took. 2003 \u2013 Football Odyssey | publisher=All Star Print Ltd. | location=Omagh, Northern Ireland | year=2004 | isbn=0-9546616-0-5 | page = 51}}</ref>\n\nOver the course of the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship 2003|2003 Championship]], he amassed a total of 1\u201348 (a total of 51 points),<ref name=Indo>{{cite news| url= http://www.unison.ie/irish_independent/stories.php3?ca=95&si=1111318&issue_id=10328 | title=Captain fantastic Canavan scoops readers' top award | accessdate= 29 April 2007 | newspaper = [[Irish Independent]] | date = 20 January 2004| postscript= <!--None-->}}</ref> and had won the National League in the spring, all of which earned him a fifth All Star.<ref name=\"AllStars\" /> Among his more notable performances of the year included an eight-point haul in the replayed first round match against [[Derry GAA|Derry]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/2003/0524/tyrone.html |title=Tyrone destroy dismal Derry |accessdate=4 March 2007 |date=24 May 2003 |publisher=[[RT\u00c9]] Sport |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605114150/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/2003/0524/tyrone.html |archivedate=5 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref> and in the replayed Ulster Final, Canavan scored eleven points.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/2003/0720/tyrone.html |title=Disappointing Down no match for silky Tyrone |accessdate=4 March 2007 |publisher=[[RT\u00c9]] Sport |date=20 July 2003 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605114204/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/2003/0720/tyrone.html |archivedate=5 June 2011 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nHe became the first GAA star to gain an honorary doctorate from the [[University of Ulster]],<ref name=UUJ /> and was also voted [[BBC Northern Ireland Sports Personality of the Year]],<ref>{{cite news| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/low/northern_ireland/3297059.stm | title=Canavan wins BBC award| accessdate=25 January 2007 | date = 6 December 2003 | publisher= [[BBC Sport]] | work=BBC News}}</ref> a regional award of the [[BBC Sports Personality of the Year]]. Following an email campaign throughout Ireland, Canavan was an early forerunner for the national award, despite the fact that Gaelic games have very little exposure in Great Britain.<ref name=buzzle>{{cite web|url=http://www.buzzle.com/editorials/12-9-2003-48440.asp |archive-url=https://archive.is/20130118181216/http://www.buzzle.com/editorials/12-9-2003-48440.asp |url-status=dead |archive-date=18 January 2013 |title=Whole of Ireland Behind Peter Canavan's BBC Sports Personality of the Year Campaign |accessdate=25 January 2007 |date=10 December 2003 }}</ref>\n\nFollowing the 2003 final, Canavan relinquished the captaincy to [[Cormac McAnallen]], but the 24-year-old died shortly after taking up the position. This tragedy adversely affected the mindset of the team, and they were unable to defend their All-Ireland.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/4130065.stm | work=BBC News | title=McAnallen death overshadows year | date=28 December 2004 | accessdate=4 May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===2005: Championship swan song===\nCanavan was used mostly as an 'impact substitute' throughout the [[All-Ireland Senior Football Championship 2005|2005 Championship]]\u2014brought on to either unsettle the opposition, or rally his teammates.<ref name=PeterBio /> This backfired when he was controversially sent off within a minute of coming on as a substitute in the [[Ulster Senior Football Championship|Ulster Final replay]] replay.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.rte.ie/sport/2005/0723/armagh.html | title=Armagh take Ulster title in scrappy affair|accessdate=4 March 2007 | publisher = [[RT\u00c9]] Sport | date = 23 July 2005}}</ref>\n\nIn the All-Ireland semi-final against [[Armagh GAA|Armagh]] (who were meeting Tyrone for the third time that year), Canavan scored with the last kick of the game, winning the match for Tyrone.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/low/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/4213594.stm | title= Armagh 1\u201312 1\u201313 Tyrone ALL-IRELAND SEMI-fINAL| accessdate=25 January 2007 | date = 4 September 2005 | work = [[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> Kevin McStay, a former [[Mayo GAA|Mayo]] player, described it as the point of the season, despite the free kick being from a relatively straightforward position.<ref>{{cite magazine| url= http://www.hoganstand.com/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=54858 | title=Kevin McStay Column | date= 21 December 2005| accessdate=2 April 2007 | magazine =[[Hogan Stand]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Canavan 2005 final goal.jpg|thumb|150px | left | Canavan (13, white) drilling home Tyrone's winning goal in the 2005 All-Ireland final]] Mickey Harte chose Canavan on the starting line-up of the All-Ireland final and went on to score Tyrone's only goal, winning on a scoreline of 1\u201316 to 2\u201310.<ref>{{cite news | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/4281008.stm | title= Tyrone triumph in Croker decider|accessdate=25 January 2007 | work = [[BBC Sport]] | date =25 September 2005}}</ref>\n\nHe retired from inter-county football following this performance with a sixth All Star, ending a sixteen-year tenure in Senior championship football.<ref>{{cite news| url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/northern_ireland/gaelic_games/4284812.stm |title= Lawn joins Canavan in retirement | accessdate=25 January 2007 | date = 26 September 2005| work = [[BBC Sport]]}}</ref> He said of his decision, \"I have spent enough time on the treatment table\", referring to the instances where he played while carrying potentially career-threatening injuries, as he had done in 1996 and 2003. Canavan's appearance in the 2005 final (his last game for Tyrone), was his forty-ninth Championship match.\n\n==Other intercounty successes==\nCanavan was part of both Tyrone sides that won the [[National Football League (Ireland)|National Football League]] title two years in a row\u2014in 2002 and 2003<ref name=PeterBio />\u2014and he competed in the 1994 final against Derry. His success in other competitions include five [[Railway Cup]]s, two Vocational Schools titles, and one [[Dr. McKenna Cup]].<ref name=TeamTalk />\n\n==Club career==\nAfter retiring from inter-county football, he continued to play at club level for [[Errigal Ciar\u00e1n]] until 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thespiritofpaulmcgirr.com/content/view/58/2/ |title=Canavan Runs for the Spirit of Paul McGirr |accessdate=20 October 2008 |work=The Spirit of Paul McGirr website |year=2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090106123316/http://thespiritofpaulmcgirr.com/content/view/58/2/ |archivedate=6 January 2009 }}</ref> During the seventeen years he played he won six [[Tyrone Senior Club Football Championship|Tyrone Senior Club]] titles and two [[Ulster Senior Club Football Championship|Ulster Club Championships]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.errigalciaran.com/club_achievements.asp |title=Errigal Ciaran achievements |accessdate=25 January 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070421135052/http://www.errigalciaran.com/club_achievements.asp |archivedate=21 April 2007 |df=dmy }}</ref> and in 2006, he won his first Tyrone All Star for his performances in the club championship.<ref>{{cite magazine |url= http://www.hoganstand.com/Tyrone/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=70439 | title=Canavan wins first Tyrone All-Star | accessdate=25 January 2007 | date = 20 December 2006 | magazine = [[Hogan Stand]] }}</ref>\nIn December 2008, he moved into management for the first time, by taking charge of Errigal Ciaran,<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.irishtimes.com/sports/gaa/2008/1229/1229728618500.html |title=Canavan to manage Errigal | accessdate = 29 December 2008 | date = 29 December 2008 | newspaper = [[The Irish Times]] | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref> leading them to win the Tyrone All County League final in 2009.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nwipp-newspapers.com/SC/free/295869823020783.php |newspaper=Ulster Herald |date=12 November 2009 |author=Kevin Kelly |title=Final flourish sees Errigal home }}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Disciplinary problems==\nHis career features many examples of indiscipline,<ref>{{Cite news | last =Keys | first =Colm | title = Tyrone ace Canavan's jaw broken | newspaper = [[Daily Mirror|The Mirror]] | pages = 36 | date= 30 April 1998 | postscript =<!--None-->}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/bbc_pundits/1564155.stm | work= [[BBC Sport]] | author = Jerome Quinn | title = Jerome Quinn: My End of Season Awards | date = 26 September 2001 | postscript = <!--None-->}}</ref> including on-pitch scuffles with other players.<ref name=Jason /> which at times threatened to overshadow his achievements. [[Jack O'Connor (Gaelic footballer)|Jack O'Connor]], [[Kerry GAA|Kerry]]'s manager in the 2005 All-Ireland final, suggested in his autobiography that Canavan tackled [[Colm Cooper]] off the ball, preventing him getting into a goal-scoring position,<ref>{{cite book\n  | last =O'Connor\n  | first =Jack\n  | authorlink = Jack O'Connor (Gaelic footballer)\n  | title =Keys to the Kingdom\n  | publisher =Penguin Ireland\n  | date= 4 July 2007\n  | isbn = 1-84488-153-9}}</ref> a claim backed up by ''[[Sunday Tribune]]'' journalist, Kieran Shannon.<ref>{{Cite news\n |last=Shannon \n |first=Keiran \n |title=A history of violence \n |newspaper=[[Sunday Tribune]] \n |pages= \n |date=12 February 2006 \n |url=http://www.tribune.ie/archive/article/2006/feb/12/a-history-of-violence/\n |format= \n |postscript= \n}}{{dead link|date=December 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Management career==\nCanavan was appointed manager of [[Fermanagh GAA|Fermanagh]] in November 2011 on a three-year term to be reviewed annually, with trainer Kieran Donnelly and selector Enda Kilpatrick joining him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2011/1121/canavanp_fermanagh.html |title=Canavan appointed Fermanagh manager |publisher=[[RT\u00c9 Sport]] |accessdate=21 November 2011 |date=21 November 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111123123335/http://www.rte.ie/sport/gaa/championship/2011/1121/canavanp_fermanagh.html |archivedate=23 November 2011 }}</ref> His first game against Antrim, saw Fermanagh winning by a scoreline of 2 \u2013 11 to 1 \u2013 06.\n\nHe stepped down as Fermanagh manager in September 2013.<ref>{{cite news|first=Colm|last=Keys|url=http://www.independent.ie/sport/gaelic-football/peter-canavan-decides-to-opt-out-after-two-years-as-fermanagh-manager-29546596.html|title=Peter Canavan decides to opt out after two years as Fermanagh manager|newspaper=Irish Independent|publisher=Independent News & Media|date=3 September 2013|accessdate=3 September 2013}}</ref>\n\nHowever, Canavan was not out of management for long. He was appointed manager of Cavan Gaels in December 2013 and guided them to their 1st Senior Championship in 3 years in October 2014, defeating Kingscourt Stars in the final by a point. This was seen as a huge success for Canavan and the Cavan Gaels Club.\n\nAfter delivering the Oliver Plunkett trophy back to the Cavan town club, he then went on to become a selector with the Tyrone under 21 panel in 2015. He was part of the management team which consisted of Fergal Logan (Manager) and Brian Dooher. They guided the under 21s to an Ulster Final victory against Donegal in Celtic Park, and subsequently, to the All Ireland title, defeating Tipperary in the final.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.hoganstand.com/Tyrone/ArticleForm.aspx?ID=50132 Hoganstand GAA Immortals]\n* [http://www.tyronegaa.ie/ Official Tyrone Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060526102917/http://www.gaelsport.com/html/club/club_home.jsp?c=586 Errigal Ciar\u00e1n Official Website]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070930165132/http://www.culturenorthernireland.org/article.aspx?co=14&ca=15&to=0&sca=0&articleID=641&navID=10 Culture Northern Ireland Biography]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-sports|gaa}}\n{{succession box\n | before=First year awarded\n | title=[[All Stars Footballer of the Year]]\n | years=1995\n | after=[[Martin O'Connell (footballer)|Martin O'Connell]]<br/>([[Meath GAA|Meath]])\n}}\n{{succession box\n | before=[[Kieran McGeeney]]<br/>([[Armagh GAA|Armagh]])\n | title=[[List of All-Ireland Senior Football Championship winning captains|All-Ireland Senior Football]]<br/>winning [[Captain (sport)|captain]]\n | years=2003\n | after=[[Dara \u00d3 Cinn\u00e9ide]]<br/>([[Kerry GAA|Kerry]])\n}}\n{{succession box\n | before=[[Kieran McGeeney]]<br/>([[Armagh GAA|Armagh]])\n | title=[[Texaco Footballer of th